For the NCD and NCD–tetracycline systems, it was calculated to be 7.60 ns and 7.57 ns, respectively, τ0/τ ≈ 1(τ0 and τ are the lifetimes of NCDs in the absence and presence of tetracycline, respectively). This finding indicates that there is no energy transfer between tetracycline and NCDs and that the possible fluorescence quenching mechanism is an inner filter effect instead of FRET. In order to further explore the quenching mechanism, the TEM images of NCDs after the addition of tetracycline were analyzed. As shown in the Fig. S4, the size of NCDs-tetracycline was larger compared to the well dispersed image of pure NCDs. From this we can infer that tetracycline molecules induced aggregation which finally resulted in the fluorescence quenching [44]. Compared to other reported works in literature, our work and proposed sensor could detect tetracycline with a lower LOD (
